My initial cold judgement, (I must do more research): - India must feel pressure to respond from negative (20 dead vs apparently zero the other side) news around this recent fight, therefore some certainty (80-90%) a response will happen;
- India is impacted by COVID-19 quite substantially and ability to recover must be the higher internal concern - will this be resolved prior to 30 Sep 2020, unlikely at present;
- China must therefore sense opportunity to seek advantage, although I feel this is more likely by taking territory or increasing infrastructure;
- India less so (from a military response rather than building infrastructure), however, Chinese PR is at quite a low from larger international community, Aus, UK, US etc.
- India would then likely over-compensate immediately if China physically escalated twice (as the Indian's see it) with back-to-back instances;
- Increase in activity from both sides makes a situation more likely than unlikely to occur;
- Could both sides benefit from this publicity as opposed to other on-going internal and external (less external for India) issues;
- I found it interesting that during this fight, no firearms were used as agreed within a treaty - even in a life and death scenario no ammunition was used beyond basic tools. Some control is there.
- India must still consider 1962 dispute as found in NYT article since China has expanded it's military capability significantly since this date, India somewhat in comparison:(https://www.nytimes.com/2020/06/19/opinion/China-India-conflict.html). Quote 'the border dispute flared into a war. China won conclusively'.
- Method of attack is interesting (from same article): India protested. On June 6, Indian and Chinese military officers started talks to de-escalate the crisis. The Chinese agreed to vacate some positions. On the evening of June 15, an Indian Army patrol set out to verify whether the Chinese had withdrawn from positions on the Indian side of the Line of Actual Control. According to the Indian officials, the Chinese had not withdrawn as agreed, and several hundred Chinese soldiers ambushed the Indian patrol. The Chinese claim they were on their own side of the Line of Actual Control when the Indian soldiers crossed over and attacked them. While both Indian and Chinese soldiers carry weapons when they patrol the border, it has been a longstanding practice, in accordance with agreements signed by the two countries in 1996 and 2005, not to use firearms during patrol clashes. Brutal hand-to-hand fighting followed in which the Chinese killed at least 20 Indian soldiers , pushing some of the wounded over the steep cliffs overlooking the Galwan River. - Conclusion:
At present, I am thinking between now and 30 Sep, both sides will aggressively build infrastructure. India will be keen to expand territory which may increase likelihood of retaliation/ further confrontation as time goes on. Side note: I must admit that the inclusion of militia in the question does make it more probable for a response from India, however, I have concluded with the increased military numbers in the area who will be keen to control any non-governmental retaliation and with COVID-19 worries, it will be difficult for any militia to insert itself, despite their probable need for 'revenge'. Please critique.
